2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: descriptive nickname from Welsh <i>llwyd</i> ‘gray’. InWelsh the color term <i>llwyd</i> also includes shades of brown, andit is likely that, when used with reference to younger men,<i>llwyd</i> denoted brown or mouse-colored hair."],"variants":[{"name":"Loyd","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Lloyd  ."]}]},{"name":"Daughter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (London): variant of <b>Dafter</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, apparently from Middle English <i>doughter</i>, <i>dohtor</i>, <i>douter</i> (Old English <i>dohtor</i>) ‘daughter’, often pronounced in early modern English as <i>dafter</i>. For the name to be borne by a man, such that it became a hereditary surname, is surprising, though there are occasional instances of men being named in this way (unless they are clerical errors or it was a surname acquired by the retainers of an heiress of an important family). Alternatively, alternatively <i>Daughter</i>, <i>Daughters</i> might be a simplified pronunciation of <b>Dawtry</b> (see   Daughtery  ), a surname well evidenced in Yorkshire and Sussex, where <i>Doughter</i> and <i>Daughter</i> also occur, in which case the change to <i>Dafter</i> will have arisen through misinterpretation."],"variants":[{"name":"Daughtery","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Dawtrey</b>, see   Daughtry   and also   Daughters  . The surname is most common in Yorkshire and Sussex, where the medieval <i>Dawtrey</i> family held lands in the 12th century."]}]},{"name":"verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]},{"name":"Rhys","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘ardour’; borne in the Middle Ages by various rulers in south-west Wales, including  Rhys ap Tewdur  (  d. 1093 ) and  Rhys ap Gruffudd  (  1132–97 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Reece","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Rhys . The name is now in widespread and frequent use outside Wales, in many cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the given name."]},{"name":"Rees","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Welsh Rhys, in some cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the Welsh given name."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Daughter verch Rhys Lloyd was born about 1320, in Caernarfonshire, Wales as the daughter of Rhys Lloyd. She had at least 2 sons with Gruffudd ap Howel."},"et":{"about 1320–":"umbes 1320–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1345–Male":"1345–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","about 1345":"umbes 1345","1340":"1340","about 1320":"umbes 1320","1280":"1280","about 1340":"umbes 1340","Creuddyn, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"about 1320–":"noin 1320–Kuollut","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1345–Male":"1345–Kuollut","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","about 1345":"noin 1345","1340":"1340","about 1320":"noin 1320","1280":"1280","about 1340":"noin 1340","Creuddyn, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales"},"fr":{"about 1320–":"environ 1320–Décédée","1320–Female":"1320–Décédée","1310–Male":"1310–Décédé","1340–Male":"1340–Décédé","1345–Male":"1345–Décédé","1280–Male":"1280–Décédé","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1320":"1320